WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.060 --> 00:00:04.990
MARIO: Welcome, everybody.

00:00:04.990 --> 00:00:07.920
Welcome to the screen
of the documentary film

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:10.430
"The Connection."

00:00:10.430 --> 00:00:12.050
And my name is
Mario [? Adetta. ?]

00:00:12.050 --> 00:00:14.811
I'm part of People Development.

00:00:14.811 --> 00:00:17.060
I'm part of the Well-Being
team in People Development.

00:00:17.060 --> 00:00:20.980
I'm also in the
core team of gPause.

00:00:20.980 --> 00:00:24.990
We are honored to have
today with us the filmmaker,

00:00:24.990 --> 00:00:28.990
the director of the film "The
Connection," Shannon Harvey,

00:00:28.990 --> 00:00:31.950
who came all the way
from Sydney, Australia.

00:00:31.950 --> 00:00:34.090
She's a journalist, filmmaker.

00:00:34.090 --> 00:00:37.830
And she's going to
introduce her film herself.

00:00:37.830 --> 00:00:39.147
Welcome to Google, Shannon.

00:00:39.147 --> 00:00:40.230
SHANNON HARVEY: Thank you.

00:00:40.230 --> 00:00:43.110
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:45.790 --> 00:00:50.820
It is a real buzz to
be here at Google HQ.

00:00:50.820 --> 00:00:53.850
We talk about it as a
legendary place in Australia.

00:00:53.850 --> 00:00:57.630
And it's absolutely incredible
to be walking around campus.

00:00:57.630 --> 00:00:59.340
I even saw somebody
on a skateboard

00:00:59.340 --> 00:01:03.900
with a laptop, which was
perfect, when I first arrived.

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:09.560
But to be talking to a room
with people who are setting

00:01:09.560 --> 00:01:13.530
the agenda for a digital
future that I cannot even begin

00:01:13.530 --> 00:01:16.990
to imagine is very humbling.

00:01:16.990 --> 00:01:20.320
And I'm very honored to be here.

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:24.280
So thank you very much.

00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:28.170
I've spent the last few years
meeting and interviewing

00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:31.760
some of the world's leading
experts in meditation,

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:35.090
in mindfulness, and
in mind-body medicine.

00:01:35.090 --> 00:01:39.270
And I've often heard them quote
from a German philosopher who

00:01:39.270 --> 00:01:43.360
lived in the 1800's named
Arthur Schopenhauer.

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:48.850
And in fact, I've based my talk
on Arthur Schopenhauer's quote.

00:01:48.850 --> 00:01:51.790
But unfortunately, as
I went through my notes

00:01:51.790 --> 00:01:54.610
to do my references yesterday,
which is something that's

00:01:54.610 --> 00:01:57.990
very important to do, as a
former journalist, I Googled.

00:01:57.990 --> 00:02:00.660
And I discovered that
there is some conjecture

00:02:00.660 --> 00:02:02.780
as to whether Arthur
Schopenhauer actually

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:04.410
said the quote.

00:02:04.410 --> 00:02:06.077
So thank you, Google.

00:02:06.077 --> 00:02:07.450
[LAUGHS]

00:02:07.450 --> 00:02:10.650
I've also discovered, though,
that many wise people have

00:02:10.650 --> 00:02:13.170
said something rather
similar-- people

00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:16.900
like William James, Arthur
C. Clarke, Elbert Hubbard.

00:02:16.900 --> 00:02:19.040
And they've said
many similar things.

00:02:19.040 --> 00:02:23.390
So the quote that I will
be basing my talk today on

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:28.110
is being attributed
to the internet.

00:02:28.110 --> 00:02:30.220
The internet once said
that, "Every truth

00:02:30.220 --> 00:02:34.560
passes through three stages
before it is recognized.

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:37.460
In the first, it is ridiculed.

00:02:37.460 --> 00:02:39.980
In the second, it is opposed.

00:02:39.980 --> 00:02:43.740
And in the third, it is
regarded as self-evident."

00:02:43.740 --> 00:02:47.140
And I'm using this quote to
talk about the acceptance

00:02:47.140 --> 00:02:50.820
of the mind-body connection.

00:02:50.820 --> 00:02:52.440
I spent the last
few years looking

00:02:52.440 --> 00:02:54.100
at how some of the
latest research

00:02:54.100 --> 00:02:58.180
from leading institutions,
like Harvard and Stanford,

00:02:58.180 --> 00:03:00.750
shows that the state
of someone's mind

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:05.050
can significantly alter
the quality of their life.

00:03:05.050 --> 00:03:07.330
It sounds revolutionary, I know.

00:03:07.330 --> 00:03:08.410
Who would have thought?

00:03:08.410 --> 00:03:12.390
But this science is also showing
that the state of your mind

00:03:12.390 --> 00:03:15.000
can influence things such
as your body's ability

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.560
to ward off
infection or a virus.

00:03:18.560 --> 00:03:22.750
And it can even influence the
outcome of a chronic illness.

00:03:22.750 --> 00:03:25.310
In fact, the very cutting
edge of this research

00:03:25.310 --> 00:03:27.140
shows that your
mind can actually

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:31.520
influence your body to a
cellular level, to your DNA,

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:33.510
and, in fact, influence
the DNA that you

00:03:33.510 --> 00:03:37.640
pass on to your children and
your children's children.

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:41.170
And it may even influence
how long you live.

00:03:41.170 --> 00:03:43.010
I want you all,
just for a moment,

00:03:43.010 --> 00:03:46.420
to imagine walking into your
doctor's room feeling tired

00:03:46.420 --> 00:03:50.870
and run down, and being given
a diagnosis of chronic fatigue,

00:03:50.870 --> 00:03:53.680
and telling your doctor
that you're self-prescribing

00:03:53.680 --> 00:03:57.390
an eight-week meditation course.

00:03:57.390 --> 00:03:59.020
You would be laughed
at and you would

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:02.710
be told to go back to your
commune in California.

00:04:02.710 --> 00:04:06.060
It is my personal mission
to take our understanding

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:08.560
of the truth of the
mind-body connection

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:13.210
from the first and second stage
of being ridiculed and opposed

00:04:13.210 --> 00:04:17.670
into the third stage of being
regarded as self-evident.

00:04:17.670 --> 00:04:20.290
And like all good
projects of passion,

00:04:20.290 --> 00:04:23.540
my enthusiasm is personal.

00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:26.490
This is a photograph
that I hate looking at.

00:04:26.490 --> 00:04:28.400
This is a photograph
of me a few years

00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:32.820
after I had been diagnosed
with an autoimmune disease.

00:04:32.820 --> 00:04:35.910
I walked into a doctor's
room at the age of 24,

00:04:35.910 --> 00:04:39.930
and I was told that he
suspected I had lupus.

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:43.840
Lupus is an autoimmune disease
where your immune system starts

00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:47.470
attacking your perfectly
normal, healthy tissue.

00:04:47.470 --> 00:04:49.810
The doctor told me
that he suspected

00:04:49.810 --> 00:04:52.020
that I may have trouble
having children.

00:04:52.020 --> 00:04:54.760
He told me that if the
disease progressed,

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:57.460
it could end up
attacking my organs.

00:04:57.460 --> 00:05:00.340
And he told me that I may
end up in a wheelchair

00:05:00.340 --> 00:05:02.980
before I turn 30.

00:05:02.980 --> 00:05:04.110
It was pretty devastating.

00:05:04.110 --> 00:05:05.800
I was a journalist.

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:08.820
I had just landed my dream job
at the Australian Broadcasting

00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:11.650
Corporation as a radio
and news journalist.

00:05:11.650 --> 00:05:14.500
And in that moment,
everything came crashing down.

00:05:20.210 --> 00:05:23.220
Unfortunately, the thing
about being diagnosed

00:05:23.220 --> 00:05:25.830
with a chronic illness
is that there's actually

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:28.460
nothing exceptional about it.

00:05:28.460 --> 00:05:31.520
In fact, according to the
World Health Organization,

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:33.770
there's more than
a one in two chance

00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:36.560
you will be diagnosed
with a chronic illness.

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:39.320
And by that, I'm talking
about cancer, diabetes,

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:42.040
heart disease, chronic
migraines, chronic back pain,

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:45.110
chronic fatigue, Crohn's
disease, fibromyalgia,

00:05:45.110 --> 00:05:47.900
multiple sclerosis--
the list goes on.

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:52.060
And it actually gets worse,
because one in four Americans

00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:55.670
will have two or more
chronic health conditions.

00:05:55.670 --> 00:05:57.930
The cost of this global
burden of disease

00:05:57.930 --> 00:06:04.150
is predicted to soar to
$47 trillion by 2030.

00:06:04.150 --> 00:06:06.100
No wonder the World
Health Organization

00:06:06.100 --> 00:06:09.330
has labeled this as
an impending disaster.

00:06:09.330 --> 00:06:11.810
And the UN Secretary
General, Ban Ki-moon,

00:06:11.810 --> 00:06:17.640
describes the rising chronic
illness as a global epidemic.

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:20.210
So there I was,
just another person

00:06:20.210 --> 00:06:23.050
saddled with a lifelong
chronic illness.

00:06:23.050 --> 00:06:26.660
But being a journalist,
I also had a deep desire

00:06:26.660 --> 00:06:29.400
to search for answers.

00:06:29.400 --> 00:06:35.460
Over a number of years, I spent
$30,000 on drugs and surgeries,

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:39.270
on alternative therapies, as
well as mainstream therapies,

00:06:39.270 --> 00:06:42.050
but I was still sick.

00:06:42.050 --> 00:06:45.970
One day, on yet
another Google search,

00:06:45.970 --> 00:06:48.220
I came across a
document that had

00:06:48.220 --> 00:06:49.970
been written for
medical students

00:06:49.970 --> 00:06:53.500
by an Australian MD
named Craig Hassed.

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:56.770
I didn't realize it at the
time, but this document

00:06:56.770 --> 00:06:59.210
was about to change my life.

00:06:59.210 --> 00:07:01.820
It was called, "Mind-Body
Medicine-- Science,

00:07:01.820 --> 00:07:04.100
Practice and Philosophy."

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:08.360
And it explained how, in
the last 5 to 10 years,

00:07:08.360 --> 00:07:12.220
the advances in technology have
allowed us to look at the ways

00:07:12.220 --> 00:07:15.940
things like the brain and the
immune system can interact

00:07:15.940 --> 00:07:18.160
in order to affect our health.

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:19.970
It was a document
that was summarizing

00:07:19.970 --> 00:07:23.420
peer-reviewed,
academic research.

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:26.990
This was evidence-based
mind-body medicine,

00:07:26.990 --> 00:07:30.790
and it was designed to target
medical students so they could

00:07:30.790 --> 00:07:34.720
apply it to their own practice.

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:36.480
It explored
research, such as how

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:39.070
the immune systems
of medical students

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:42.660
became profoundly
suppressed before or just

00:07:42.660 --> 00:07:44.920
after an exam period.

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:47.500
But if they were taught
relaxation techniques,

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:50.630
they showed significantly
better immune function

00:07:50.630 --> 00:07:53.460
and less illness during exams.

00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:56.410
It looked at how merely
seeing your doctor coming

00:07:56.410 --> 00:07:58.520
at you to take
your blood pressure

00:07:58.520 --> 00:08:00.860
could make your
blood pressure rise.

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:03.420
And as a result, a
quarter of people

00:08:03.420 --> 00:08:07.060
are being misdiagnosed
with hypertension.

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:10.420
It looked at how a chronic
or long-term activation

00:08:10.420 --> 00:08:14.090
of your stress response, your
fight or flight response,

00:08:14.090 --> 00:08:16.870
leads to what's called
allostatic load, which

00:08:16.870 --> 00:08:20.750
is associated with type
2 diabetes, obesity,

00:08:20.750 --> 00:08:24.440
hypertension, atrophy of the
nerve cells in your brain.

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:26.042
Stress is bad for you.

00:08:26.042 --> 00:08:27.000
Who would have thought?

00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:33.690
But before I elaborate
a little bit further,

00:08:33.690 --> 00:08:37.110
there is something that I want
to clarify and make very, very

00:08:37.110 --> 00:08:38.610
clear.

00:08:38.610 --> 00:08:42.340
The research and my
film is not saying

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:46.910
that mental wellness is more
important than nutrition,

00:08:46.910 --> 00:08:51.040
than exercise, than drugs,
and surgeries, and the wonders

00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:53.110
of modern medicine.

00:08:53.110 --> 00:08:55.900
But it is saying that
the state of your mind

00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:59.160
is extremely important.

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:03.290
Dr. Hassed's document led me
to the work of Jon Kabat-Zinn.

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:06.030
And some of you who have done
the Search Inside Yourself

00:09:06.030 --> 00:09:07.670
program here at
Google would know

00:09:07.670 --> 00:09:11.020
that this has been an
influence on the program.

00:09:11.020 --> 00:09:14.640
Dr. Kabat-Zinn has been
instrumental in introducing

00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:18.950
stress reduction and meditation
into a medical setting.

00:09:18.950 --> 00:09:21.250
And he initially
found that people

00:09:21.250 --> 00:09:24.440
who meditated while receiving
light therapy to treat

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:28.150
psoriasis healed four
times faster than people

00:09:28.150 --> 00:09:29.150
who were non-meditators.

00:09:31.950 --> 00:09:34.560
I also came across the
work of Dr. Dean Ornish

00:09:34.560 --> 00:09:36.600
from the University
of California,

00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:38.580
whose mind-body
programs have proven

00:09:38.580 --> 00:09:42.310
that people with heart
disease and prostate cancer

00:09:42.310 --> 00:09:44.800
can actually be
treated, sometimes

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:46.570
without drugs or surgery.

00:09:46.570 --> 00:09:49.000
In some cases, his
program has been

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:52.970
able to slow the progression
of these illnesses

00:09:52.970 --> 00:09:55.160
or even reverse them.

00:09:55.160 --> 00:09:58.330
In fact, he recently joined
with a major health insurer

00:09:58.330 --> 00:09:59.880
here in the US.

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:04.300
And surprise, surprise, they
found that the participants

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:07.330
had significantly
improved health outcomes.

00:10:07.330 --> 00:10:09.500
But when the insurer looked
at the dollars and cents

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:12.690
of the program, it reported
cutting their customer's health

00:10:12.690 --> 00:10:17.130
care costs by half
in the first year.

00:10:17.130 --> 00:10:20.260
Dr. Ornish's program
includes stress management

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:24.230
through yoga and
meditation, a healthy diet,

00:10:24.230 --> 00:10:28.500
moderate exercise,
and social support.

00:10:28.500 --> 00:10:31.650
These are not expensive things.

00:10:31.650 --> 00:10:34.100
So I started applying some
of the research findings

00:10:34.100 --> 00:10:36.450
that I was reading
about to my own life.

00:10:36.450 --> 00:10:39.890
And over a number of years, I
developed a regular meditation

00:10:39.890 --> 00:10:41.610
and yoga practice.

00:10:41.610 --> 00:10:44.850
I changed my perception
of my work stress.

00:10:44.850 --> 00:10:47.370
I learned about
balancing my emotions.

00:10:47.370 --> 00:10:51.780
And I moved much closer to
my family and my friends.

00:10:51.780 --> 00:10:55.240
I started feeling
more and more well.

00:10:55.240 --> 00:10:57.800
And despite my
original prognosis,

00:10:57.800 --> 00:11:02.950
I am very happy to say that I am
the proud mother of a baby boy.

00:11:02.950 --> 00:11:05.570
And recently, just
a few weeks ago,

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:08.710
I had a routine blood
test that showed

00:11:08.710 --> 00:11:13.260
no sign of autoimmune
disease in my body.

00:11:13.260 --> 00:11:17.850
Although our doctors and our
health practitioners mean well,

00:11:17.850 --> 00:11:20.260
most people like me,
with a chronic illness,

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:23.710
are being offered little more
than a bill, a prescription

00:11:23.710 --> 00:11:28.460
for drugs or surgery,
and another appointment.

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:31.680
But I'm living proof of the
power of mind-body medicine,

00:11:31.680 --> 00:11:34.080
and I am far from unique.

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:35.930
In my film, which
you're about to see,

00:11:35.930 --> 00:11:38.500
you will see the
stories of other people

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:42.510
who have, in one way or another,
had their health affected

00:11:42.510 --> 00:11:44.650
by the state of their mind.

00:11:44.650 --> 00:11:48.170
You will see the story
of Dr. Craig Duncan.

00:11:48.170 --> 00:11:50.850
He's a leading sports
scientist in Australia

00:11:50.850 --> 00:11:54.220
who is responsible for the
health and the well-being

00:11:54.220 --> 00:11:56.350
of our late footballers.

00:11:56.350 --> 00:12:00.310
He was a vegetarian, and he
was as fit as the athletes

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:01.980
that he trains.

00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:05.240
But he had a heart attack during
an extremely stressful time

00:12:05.240 --> 00:12:06.700
in his life.

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:09.700
As he says in the
film, "It doesn't

00:12:09.700 --> 00:12:13.820
matter how healthy your
body is if your mind isn't

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:16.500
in some sort of balance."

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:19.630
You'll also see the story of
Professor George Jelinek, who

00:12:19.630 --> 00:12:22.360
is a leading Australian
medical doctor.

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:24.400
To give you an idea of
this man's credentials,

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:27.380
he has written the medical
textbooks for emergency

00:12:27.380 --> 00:12:29.570
medicine and is the
inaugural editor

00:12:29.570 --> 00:12:33.070
of a major medical
journal that specializes

00:12:33.070 --> 00:12:35.370
in emergency medicine.

00:12:35.370 --> 00:12:38.220
His story is perhaps the
most compelling of them all.

00:12:38.220 --> 00:12:41.530
And he's my personal hero,
because he has not only

00:12:41.530 --> 00:12:44.760
recovered from
multiple sclerosis,

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:47.030
but he's also developed
a program that

00:12:47.030 --> 00:12:50.770
is seeing many other people
recover from multiple sclerosis

00:12:50.770 --> 00:12:51.990
as well.

00:12:51.990 --> 00:12:55.140
This is an illness that
traditional medicine

00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:57.730
has no cure for.

00:12:57.730 --> 00:13:02.930
And yet, often, when these
people tell their stories,

00:13:02.930 --> 00:13:07.270
they are met with cynicism, and
they are met with opposition.

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:10.030
Mind-body medicine
is sadly considered

00:13:10.030 --> 00:13:12.390
California hippie juju.

00:13:12.390 --> 00:13:15.680
Doctors weren't taught it
in medical school years ago.

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:19.530
Therefore, they say
it doesn't work.

00:13:19.530 --> 00:13:22.640
20 years ago, the notion
that group support

00:13:22.640 --> 00:13:25.740
would improve the outcome
for women with breast cancer

00:13:25.740 --> 00:13:27.780
was considered ridiculous.

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:32.160
But Dr. David Spiegel from
Stanford is proving just that.

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:34.900
10 years ago, if someone
had said that meditation

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:38.880
can flip the switch on genes
affecting disease, which

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:41.640
has now been proven to
be true by Dr. Herbert

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:45.990
Benson from Harvard, they would
have been violently opposed.

00:13:45.990 --> 00:13:49.000
Even to this day, when
I talk about the latest

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:50.880
research coming
from institutions

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:54.780
all over the world, looking
at the ritual of medicine

00:13:54.780 --> 00:13:58.410
and how the interaction
between a patient and a doctor

00:13:58.410 --> 00:14:03.430
can significantly alter the
way a sick person's body reacts

00:14:03.430 --> 00:14:07.970
to an illness, I am met
with skepticism, opposition,

00:14:07.970 --> 00:14:10.110
and sometimes outrage.

00:14:10.110 --> 00:14:13.650
The science has shown us
that things like meditation,

00:14:13.650 --> 00:14:16.620
mindfulness, emotional
intelligence, and stress

00:14:16.620 --> 00:14:20.810
reduction make us happier,
healthier, stronger,

00:14:20.810 --> 00:14:22.740
and smarter.

